50|$|After leaving staff unpaid {{for several}} months, in September 2014, the studio {{announced}} {{a reduction in}} workforce of 90%. The closure of TRC Family Entertainment caused a political storm, between the Malta Labour Party and the Nationalist party. The Economy Minister Chris Cardona asked the opposition to shoulder responsibility for investing in TRC despite <b>due</b> <b>diligence</b> <b>exercises</b> uncovering the company’s “links to criminal activity”. In parliament the minister asked the opposition why the directors have given themselves €1.7 million in director fees even though the company did not generate any money. The Prime Minister Joseph Muscat added that the founders {{had a history of}} unsuccessful businesses. He also highlighted that although in businesses bankruptcy was always a risk, the opposition had access to the <b>due</b> <b>diligence</b> report.|$|R
